node.text:
Today was Day 10 at the Paralympics, where a record number of 86 countries have now won medals.⁠⁠
Pakistan became the latest nation to enjoy success when Haiden Ali’s powerful discus performance earned his nation’s first-ever gold, while at the other end of the scale Jessica Long collected her 28th medal for the USA.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
That tally will be even more incredible should she keep competing into her fifties, something Keiko Sugiura is successfully doing as she won her second gold in her home Games in the C1-3 road race.⁠⁠
We can’t believe there are only two days left – what are you most excited to see over the weekend?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Keep up to date with all of the action, as well as everything else going on in Tokyo, via the link in our bio.⁠⁠

node.text:
Most athletes dream of stepping onto the podium. @janja_garnbret dreamt of climbing to the top of it. 🧗‍♀️⁠⁠
⁠⁠
As a kid, she was always scaling trees or door frames in her family home. She couldn’t be removed from her local climbing wall back then, and now she cannot be removed from the summit of her sport.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Having won numerous world championships, her spot in climbing’s history was secured by becoming the sport’s first female Olympic gold medalist with a dominating performance at #Tokyo2020. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠

node.text:
Day Nine at the Paralympics was dominated by women taking their sports to new heights.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Dame Sarah Storey’s 17th gold made her Great Britain’s most decorated Paralympian, Jiang Yuyan blew the field away in the 400m freestyle S6 and Vanessa Low incredibly broke the long jump T63 world record three times on her way to gold.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
But the most precious metal of all was presented to Cape Verde athlete, Keula Nidreia Pereira Semedo, who got engaged to her guide Manuel Antonio Vaz de Veiga after the 200m T11. 🇨🇻 💙⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You can keep up to date with all of the action, as well as everything else going on in Tokyo, via the link in our bio.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#Tokyo2020 #Paralympics

node.text:
Like any marathon, Eliud Kipchoge's journey has been a long and arduous one. 🏃⁠
⁠
It all started with a five-month quest to make enough money as a milkman to buy his first pair of running shoes. These days, he delivers gold medals. ⁠
⁠
At #Tokyo2020, he became the first person to retain an Olympic marathon title in over 40 years, finishing 80 seconds ahead of his nearest rival. 🥇⁠
⁠
Hit the link in bio to watch his #marathon highlights. ⁠
⁠
#Tokyo2020 | #ShiningStars⁠
